article.headline: Kent St. 68, Buffalo 64
article.story: KENT, Ohio (AP) -- Haminn Quaintance had a dunk in the final seconds Wednesday night to help Kent State take a 68-64 win over Buffalo. Kent was ahead 66-61 when Eric Moore hit a 3-pointer to bring the Bulls within two with 36 seconds left, but Quaintance's dunk 33 seconds later sealed the win. Quaintance came off the bench to lead the Golden Flashes (18-9, 10-3 Mid-American) with 11 points and eight rebounds. Omni Smith also scored 11 from off the bench, and Jordan Mincy had a game-high 10 assists. Byron Mulkey had a game-high 21 points, hitting four of his eight 3-point attempts, for the Bulls (11-16, 3-10). Yassin Idbihi scored 13, going 7-of-8 on free throws, and had 11 rebounds. Moore came off the bench score 12, all on 3-pointers. Kent was ahead by as many as nine points in game that saw five lead changes in the first half. Kent took a 32-31 lead into half time and never relinquished the lead after the break. Kent shot about 47 percent (25-of-53) from the floor to about 36 percent (21-of-59) for Buffalo. Kent also held a 13-8 advantage on points off turnovers and scored 38 points in the paint to the Bulls' 10.
